        <h1>E-gov Question Bank 2078 - 2078</h1>
        <p><strong>Full Marks:</strong> 60 + 20 + 20</p>
        <p><strong>Pass Marks:</strong> 24 + 8 + 8</p>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> 3 hours</p>
    <h2>Section A: Attempt any two questions.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Why do we need E-Governance? How can we use E-Governance to provide efficient services to citizens? Explain using suitable example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>We need e-governance for the following reasons:</p>
<p>1. Increase efficiency and effectiveness of government works.</p>
<p>2. Smoother and faster delivery of govt works like distributing ID Cards, Citizenship certificates, and Issuing clearances to documents (land, Tax)</p>
<p>3. Direct accessibility for the citizens</p>
<p>4. Pro-active participation of Government representatives, Bureaucrats, and citizens</p>
<p>5. No Favouritism and Nepotism</p>
<p>6. Accountability</p>
<p>7. Increase Transparency</p>
<p>8. No Need to involve third parties by paying more money than required</p>
<p>9. Communication between citizens</p>
<p>10. To make govt officials respectful, responsible, and dutiful.</p>
<p>We use E-Govemance to provide efficient services to citizens. The eGovernment&#8217;s ultimate objective is to offer an enhanced portfolio of public services efficiently and cost-effectively to citizens. The e-government also could provide more transparency for the government, it enables the public to be informed about what the government is working on and the policies which are enforced. The primary benefit would replacing and optimizing the PaperBased System while implementing electronic government. That could save lots of time, money, and also the environment in return due to reducing paper consumption. The implementation of e-government could also promote better communication between government and business. For example, e-procurement as a subsidiary of e-government services could facilitate Communication between G2G and B2B that will allow smaller businesses to Compete with bigger companies in public tenders. Hence the benefit of e-government could be creating an open and transparent market and a stronger economy. Nowadays, companies and people can get information quicker and at any moment of the day in comparison to the past. E-government and its capacity could be available to all people regardless of their place or social level. In summary, more efficiency, enhanced services to better serve citizens, better accessibility of public services, and more transparency and accountability of government services are the expected advantages of e-government.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>What is E-Governance model? Explain broadcasting/wider dissemination model and critical flow model in detail.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>E-governance models are the frameworks of digital governance that are based on the inherent characteristics of ICT such as enabling equal access to information to anyone who is a part of the digital network and de-concentration of information across the entire sources of digital network, connecting all information. The information does not reside on any particular node but flows equally across all the nodes in the E-Governance Model.</p>
<p><strong>Broadcasting/wider dissemination model </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The broadcasting model is based on the mass dissemination of governance-related information which is already available in the public domain into the wider public domain using ICTs.</li>
<li>This raises awareness among the citizens about ongoing governance processes and government services that are available to them and how they can benefit from them.</li>
<li>The application of this model using appropriate technologies, could reduce the &#8220;information failure situations&#8221;.</li>
<li>The wider-dissemination model opens up an alternate channel for people to access information as well as validates information available in the local domain from external sources.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Applications</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Putting government laws and legislation online.</li>
<li>Making available the names, contact addresses, emails, and fax no&#8217;s of local government officials online.</li>
<li>Making available key information pertaining to governmental plans, and budgets.</li>
<li>Putting key quote judgment/judicial statements that are of value to common citizens and creating our precedence for future actions online, viz. Key environment-related judgments, state v/s citizen court rulings, etc.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Merits:</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>It enhances the &#8216;access&#8217; and &#8216;flow&#8217; of information to all segments of society.</li>
<li>Government can use this model to provide greater governance services to their constituencies and to enhance the participation of citizens in governance processes.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Demerits:</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>The model can lose its effectiveness</li>
<li>In the situation of optimal ignorance</li>
<li>In societies, where the free flow of information is not possible.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Critical flow model </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The model is based on broadcasting information of &#8216;critical&#8217; value (which by its very nature will not be disclosed by those involved with bad governance practices) to a targeted audience using ICTs and other tools. The targeted audience may include media, affected parties, opposition parties, the judicial bench, independent investigators, or the general public.</li>
<li>Those who would divulge(reveal) such information could include upright officials and workers, whistleblowers, affected parties, and those who were themselves involved in bad governance practices but have now changed their minds or may wish to trade such information for lenient(soft) punishments</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Applications :</strong></p>
<p>This model could be applied in the following possible ways :</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Making available corruption-related data about a particular Ministry / Division/ Officials online to its electoral constituency or to the concerned regulatory body.</li>
<li>Making available Research studies, Enquiry reports, and Impact studies commissioned by the Government or Independent commissions to the affected parties.</li>
<li>Making Human Rights Violations cases violations freely available to Judiciary, NGOs, and concerned citizens.</li>
<li>Making available information that is usually suppressed, for instance, Environmental Information on radioactivity spills, effluents discharge, and information on green ratings of the company to the concerned community.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Merits :</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>This model is more directed and evolved.</li>
<li>Different organizations can use it differently depending on the aspect of governance and the situation they want to address.</li>
<li>The model corrects information failure, raises awareness about bad governance practices, and acts as a hindrance to bad governance practices.</li>
<li>Also, the model exerts indirect pressure on the concerned governance institution / policy-making body to move away from an optimal ignorance attitude to reform and take into cognizance the interest and opinion of the masses in decision-making processes.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Demerits :</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The model may not work in cases where the governance mechanism does not allow public debates and opinions and censures all information of critical nature.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Why do we need IT infrastructure to implement E-Governance? Explain network and computing infrastructure needed to implement E-governance.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>IT infrastructure is crucial for the implementation of e-governance because it forms the backbone of digital transformation and enables governments to deliver efficient and accessible services to citizens. It supports the development of digital platforms, websites, and applications through which citizens can access government information and interact with services.  Additionally, IT infrastructure facilitates the collection, storage, processing, and analysis of data, ensuring its security, privacy, and integrity. It also provides the necessary connectivity and communication channels for government entities to collaborate, share information, and engage with citizens. Without robust IT infrastructure, e-governance initiatives would struggle to function effectively and provide the convenience, efficiency, and transparency that citizens expect in the digital age.</p>
<p><strong>Network Infrastructure for E-Commerce </strong></p>
<p>The network infrastructure is the underlying foundation of the system. It forms the services that create the operating makeup of your network. In a Communications Services deployment, determining your network infrastructure from the project goals ensures that you will have an architecture that can scale and grow.</p>
<p><strong>The Existing Network </strong></p>
<p>We need to understand our existing network infrastructure to determine how well it can meet the needs of our deployment goals. We identify if we need to upgrade the existing network&#8217;s components or purchase new network components by examining our existing infrastructure. We should build up a complete map of the existing network by covering these areas:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>Physical communication links, such as cable length, grade, and so forth</li>
<li>Communication links, such as analog, ISDN, VPN, T3, and so forth, and available bandwidth and latency between sites.</li>
<li>server information, including Hostnames, IP addresses, Domain Name System (DNS) server for domain membership</li>
<li>Locations of devices on your network, including Hubs, Switches, Modems, Routers and bridges, and Proxy servers.</li>
<li>Number of users at each site, including mobile users</li>
</ol>
<p>After completing this inventory, you need to review that information in conjunction with your project goals to determine what changes are required so that you can successfully deliver the deployment.</p>
<p><strong>Network Infrastructure Components </strong></p>
<p>Following common network infrastructure components have a direct impact on the success of your deployment: Routers and switches, Firewalls, Load balancers, Storage Area Networks (SAN), DNS,</p>
<p><strong>Planning Your Network Infrastructure Layout </strong></p>
<p>In deriving your infrastructure topology, you need to consider the following topics: Intranet, Internal network, Proxies, Firewall Configuration, Mobile users</p>
<p><strong>Computing infrastructure </strong></p>
<p>Computing Infrastructure provides management and support for end-user computers, servers, storage systems, operating systems, databases, middleware, and ERP systems. Three groups• make up the Computing Infrastructure team:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Database and ERP Administration</li>
<li>End-User Computing</li>
<li>Server &amp; Storage Services</li>
</ul>
<p>The Computing Infrastructure team has a vast collective set of skills and expertise in areas such as data center management, Storage Area Networks, desktop and server imaging, database administration, and general troubleshooting skills.</p>
</div>
<h2>Section B: Attempt any eight questions.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Define E-Government. Explain E-Government as an Information System.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>E-Government, also known as electronic government, refers to the use of information and communication technologies (ICT) to transform and improve the delivery of government services, processes, and interactions. It involves the digitalization of administrative procedures, the utilization of online platforms, and the integration of technology into governance practices. E-Government aims to enhance the efficiency, transparency, accessibility, and citizen-centricity of government operations, allowing citizens and businesses to interact with government entities electronically, access services online, and participate in decision-making processes.</p>
<p>E-Government can be viewed as an information system that leverages technology to facilitate the exchange, storage, processing, and management of information within a government context. It comprises various components that work together to support e-governance initiatives. These components include:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Hardware:</strong> The physical infrastructure such as computers, servers, networking devices, and mobile devices that enable data processing and communication.</li>
<li><strong>Software:</strong> Applications, systems, and databases that support e-governance operations, including government portals, service platforms, data management systems, and security software.</li>
<li><strong>Data:</strong> The information collected, stored, and processed within e-government systems, including citizen data, administrative records, policies, and public information.</li>
<li><strong>Networks:</strong> The connectivity infrastructure that enables communication and data exchange between government entities, citizens, and businesses, including the internet, intranets, and secure communication channels.</li>
<li><strong>People:</strong> The users and stakeholders involved in e-governance, including government officials, employees, citizens, businesses, and technology experts.</li>
</ul>
<p>As an information system, e-government facilitates the digital transformation of government processes, automates administrative tasks, enables online service delivery, supports data-driven decision-making, and promotes citizen engagement.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Why is it necessary to implement ICT in government? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Implementing ICT (Information and Communication Technology) in government is necessary due to several compelling reasons. Firstly, it enhances efficiency by automating administrative processes and enabling streamlined data management. This reduces paperwork, bureaucratic delays, and manual errors, resulting in faster decision-making and improved operational efficiency within government agencies. ICT tools also facilitate collaboration, communication, and coordination among different government entities, enabling more effective and integrated governance.</p>
<p>ICT in government significantly improves service delivery to citizens. Digital platforms, online portals, and mobile applications allow citizens to access government information, submit applications, and receive services remotely and conveniently. This eliminates the need for physical visits, reduces waiting times, and enhances accessibility to government services. Additionally, ICT enables governments to provide personalized and citizen-centric services, addressing individual needs and preferences. This leads to greater satisfaction and a positive user experience.</p>
<p>ICT implementation promotes transparency, accountability, and citizen participation. Digital platforms and open data initiatives make government information and data more accessible to the public. Citizens can access information on government policies, decisions, and spending, fostering transparency and enabling public scrutiny. ICT also facilitates citizen engagement through mechanisms such as online feedback, participatory decision-making, and digital communication channels. This empowers citizens, enhances trust in government, and strengthens democratic processes.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>What is E-Government maturity model? Describe the various maturity levels.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Realized<br />
&#8211; This level corresponds to the stage when the organization actually realizes the complete<br />
e-governance plan.<br />
&#8211; Consequently, an integrated system is established where all the internal processes of<br />
the organization are computerized and there is seamless information exchange among<br />
all concerned entities.<br />
&#8211; The organization starts delivering the services to its external as well as internal<br />
customers/users in an effective manner.<br />
&#8211; Complete realization of the plan, in a single instance, would entail enormous amount of<br />
resources in terms of time, money and manpower, which may necessitate adopting a<br />
phases approach for operation of the e-governance services.<br />
Institutionalized<br />
&#8211; At this level, the organizations sustain the realized state over a period of time so that egovernance becomes part of its work culture.<br />
&#8211; The e-governance services are effectively utilized and accepted by the users.<br />
&#8211; Several iterations between planned and realized state lead to institutionalization, when<br />
e-governance becomes a way of life.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>How can we achieve good governance through E-Government models? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>We can achieve good governance through e-governance in the following ways:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Roles and responsibilities:</strong> There should be clarity regarding individual responsibilities, organizational expectations of executives, and the role of executive and steering committees.</li>
<li><strong>Structure and composition:</strong> An executive committee needs to have the right group of people, having particular regard for each individual&#8217;s background, skills, and experience, and how the addition of individuals builds the collective capability and effective functioning of the committee.</li>
<li><strong>Purpose and strategy:</strong> The executive committee plays an important role in setting the vision, purpose, and strategies of the organization, helping the organization understand these, and adapting the plans to implement them.</li>
<li><strong>Risk management</strong>: By putting in place an appropriate system of risk oversight and internal controls, executive committees can help increase the likelihood that their organizations will deliver on their purpose.</li>
<li><strong>Organizational performance:</strong> The executive committee determines and assesses appropriate performance categories and indicators for organization.</li>
<li><strong>Committee effectiveness:</strong> An executive committee&#8217;s effectiveness may be greatly enhanced through careful planning of board-related activities; committee meetings being run efficiently; regular assessments of organizational performance; having an executive succession plan; and the effective use of sub-committees, where appropriate.</li>
<li><strong>Accountability:</strong> The executive committee must ensure there is a flow of information to the board that aids decision-making; there is transparency and accountability to external. stakeholders and employees throughout the enterprise and the integrity of financial statements and other key information is safeguarded.</li>
<li><strong>Organizational maturity:</strong> The executive committee has a role to play in enhancing the capacity and capabilities of the organization they serve.</li>
<li><strong>Culture and ethics:</strong> The executive committee sets the tone for ethical and responsible decision-making throughout the organization.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Define E-readiness. What is data system infrastructural preparedness and technological infrastructural preparedness?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>E-Readiness is the ability to use information and communication technologies (ICT) to develop one&#8217;s economy and foster one&#8217;s welfare. It is the ability to pursue value-creation opportunities facilitated by the use of the Internet. It is a measure of the e-business environment, a collection of factors that indicate how amenable (willing) a market is to Internet-based opportunities.</p>
<p><strong>Data System Infrastructural Preparedness </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>The core of e-governance is e-MIS which holds the entire database of any organization.</li>
<li>The data that were managed manually need to be computerized or brought into electronic form which means that the preparedness of a computerized database or data warehouse is required.</li>
<li>Data quality and data security are of prime concern here as most of the government infrastructures are not up to the mark in developing countries.</li>
<li>The major question that arises here is &#8220;Are all the requisite management information systems, records, databases, and work processes in the proper place so as to provide the quantity and quality of data to support the move to e-governance?&#8221;</li>
<li>This is the core computerization activity of a government process which may take several years to reach this stage.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Technological Infrastructural Preparedness </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Technology is fast changing in the ICT domain and there is a rapid obsolescence of software as well as hardware which require great financial support time and again.</li>
<li>Government organizations encounter this situation especially as their procedures to procure hardware or software are very inefficient and slow.</li>
<li>The technological infrastructure in developing countries including computing and telecommunication is absent. As a result software and hardware may not be compatible. The major reasons are the cost of technology, Adaptability, and Obsolescence (undesirable) . This is a serious limitation of e-governance implementation.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What are different approaches to E-Governance security? Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Security is one of the most important issues in E-governance. All of the security approaches that are common in E-commerce are applicable to E-governance. But E-governance is a little different from E-commerce. Usually, government networks can communicate to each other better than business networks, because, most of them are connected for transferring information, but businesses are competitors and they don&#8217;t disclose their sensitive information, so the security of E-government is much more important as compared to E-commerce. Today the users or programmers (Hackers or abusers!) are very smart and intelligent, and they can attack in several forms and so the defense level has to be sufficiently strong and comprehensive.</p>
<p>Some approaches to E-governance security are:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Security at the User Level </strong></li>
</ul>
<p>Security at the user level is a very important issue. We can classify user-level security management into three parts:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Identity Management</strong>&#8211; The main purpose of this is to create a unique digital identity or credential for all legal users by providing a unique username and password, to create and manage ICT systems that ensure that the digital identities are secure.</li>
<li><strong>Access Management System</strong>&#8211; In this level, the unique credentials which are provided to the user at the identity level are matched to identify the user, that he/she is actually an authentic person.</li>
<li><strong>Interaction Management System</strong>&#8211; Interaction management is a most comprehensive and complex phase. It includes assurance of the Integrity, Confidentiality, and Non-repudiation principles of comprehensive security.</li>
</ol>
<p>At the user level, we can use various tools such as digital identity tokens, public key infrastructure (PKI), digital signatures, asymmetric key cryptography, etc. to provide or enhance security at the user level.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Security at the Transport Level </strong></li>
</ul>
<p>At this level, we consider e-governance security in two aspects which are security within LAN and WAN, and the second one is Security over the Internet. This security level is classified into two systems, i.e. Secure Communication System and Cryptographic System.</p>
<p>The data and information reach through user to ICT assets or vice-versa, and when the data is in between these two i.e. in transmission medium which can be either LAN, WAN, or any wireless or any other medium, then we need higher security. For this e-governance, administrators use various tools or techniques like creating a Virtual Private Network (VPN), installing Firewalls, Antiviruses, and using higher and more complex Encryption or decryption techniques, etc.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain the uses of data warehousing and data mining in health, education and the rural development.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The <strong>data warehouse</strong> is an integrated collection of data extracted from operational, historical, and external databases that have been cleaned, transformed, and cataloged for retrieval and analysis to provide business intelligence for business decision-making.</p>
<p><strong>Rural Development:  </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>By analyzing data related to infrastructure needs, population demographics, and economic indicators, data warehousing and data mining can inform decisions regarding the allocation of resources for rural development projects. This enables governments and organizations to plan and implement infrastructure projects that address the specific needs of rural communities. Data on individuals below the poverty line can be built into a data warehouse.</li>
<li>Drinking water census data (from the drinking water mission) can be effectively utilized by OLAP (Online Analytical Processing) and data mining technologies.</li>
<li>Monitoring and analysis of progress made on the implementation of rural development programs can also be made using OLAP and data mining technologies.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Health: </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Data warehousing and data mining can be used to store and analyze vast amounts of health-related data, such as patient records, clinical trials, and medical literature. Researchers can leverage this data to identify patterns, correlations, and insights that contribute to medical research, drug development, and treatment advancements.</li>
<li>Community needs assessment data, immunization data, and data from national programs on controlling blindness, leprosy, and malaria can all be used for data warehousing implementation, OLAP, and data mining applications.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Education: </strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Data warehousing and data mining can be used to collect and analyze data on student performance, attendance, and behavior. This enables educators to identify patterns, trends, and factors that influence student success. The insights gained can inform interventions, personalized learning strategies, and targeted support programs to improve educational outcomes.</li>
<li>Data warehousing and data mining support learning analytics, which involves analyzing student data and interactions within learning management systems, online platforms, and educational applications. This data helps educators understand student engagement, learning patterns, and areas where students may need additional support or intervention.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>How can we use human resource management software to support E-Government?  Explain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Human resource management (HRM) software can play a vital role in supporting e-government initiatives by streamlining and optimizing human resource processes and functions. Here&#8217;s how HRM software can contribute to e-government:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Efficient Workforce Management:</strong> HRM software enables efficient management of government employees, including recruitment, onboarding, performance management, and training. It automates administrative tasks such as employee data management, leave and attendance tracking, and performance evaluations. This streamlines HR processes, reduces paperwork, and increases efficiency in managing the government workforce.</li>
<li><strong>Enhanced Employee Self-Service:</strong> HRM software often includes employee self-service portals or mobile These platforms allow government employees to access their personal information, update their profiles, apply for leave, view payslips, and access relevant HR policies and documents. By providing self-service capabilities, HRM software reduces the administrative burden on HR departments, empowers employees with direct access to information, and enhances overall employee experience and satisfaction.</li>
<li><strong>Data Integration and Analytics:</strong> HRM software can integrate with other e-government systems, such as payroll, finance, and performance management systems, to ensure seamless data flow and consistency. This integration enables the generation of comprehensive reports and analytics on workforce demographics, performance metrics, training needs, and employee satisfaction.</li>
</ol>
<p>By leveraging HRM software as part of e-government initiatives, government entities can streamline HR processes, improve workforce management, and enhance employee experiences. The automation of administrative tasks, employee self-service capabilities, and data-driven insights contribute to efficient HR operations and effective utilization of human resources. This ultimately supports the goals of e-governance by promoting transparency, efficiency, and citizen-centric service delivery.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on:</p>
<p>a. Electronic service delivery</p>
<p>b. IT in judiciary</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Electronic service delivery:</strong> Electronic service delivery (ESD) in e-governance refers to the provision of government services to citizens and businesses through digital channels, such as online platforms, mobile applications, and electronic means. Through online platforms and mobile applications, individuals can access government services anytime and from anywhere with internet connectivity. This eliminates the need for physical visits to government offices, reduces waiting times, and expands service availability to remote areas. ESD can lead to cost savings for both citizens and government entities. Citizens save on transportation costs and avoid time off from work for physical visits to government offices. From the government&#8217;s perspective, ESD reduces the need for physical infrastructure, paperwork, and manual processing, resulting in operational cost savings. Some examples of ESD are Online Tax Filing, Online Payments, Billing, etc.</p>
<p><strong>IT in Judiciary:  </strong></p>
<p>Information Technology (IT) plays a crucial role in the judiciary, transforming the way courts and legal systems operate. An example of IT in the Judiciary is a case management system. IT enables the implementation of electronic case management systems, which digitally store and manage case-related information, documents, and records. These systems streamline court processes, facilitate efficient scheduling and tracking of cases, and enable judges, lawyers, and other stakeholders to access case information electronically. Case management systems improve the efficiency of court operations, reduce paperwork, and enhance transparency and accountability.</p>
</div>
</body></html>